<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="user-story-mapping">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>product</group>
    <domain>product-manager</domain>
    <summary>Two-dimensional map: backbone left-to-right (journey), tasks vertical (priority). Exposes walking skeleton and release slices, making scope visual and defensible.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>user-stories</tag>
      <tag>mapping</tag>
      <tag>release-planning</tag>
      <tag>journey</tag>
      <tag>mvp</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>User Story Mapping</title>
    <summary>Arrange user stories into a two-dimensional map: backbone activities run left-to-right (user journey), tasks are stacked vertically under each activity by priority. The map exposes a "walking skeleton" (one task per activity, end-to-end) and horizontal release slices, making scope decisions visual and defensible. Use verb phrases for backbone items; 5-10 activities is the target range.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Flat backlogs lose journey context — stories get prioritized without seeing the full picture, critical steps disappear, and release scope becomes guesswork. A story map forces the team to answer "How does our backlog connect to the user's journey?" before committing to a release. The walking skeleton also defines the earliest defensible MVP boundary, making it the foundation for all subsequent slicing decisions.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Decomposing a new product or major feature where the user journey spans 3+ steps and the team needs a shared mental model.</item>
        <item>Slicing releases from a large feature backlog by identifying a walking skeleton then incremental slices.</item>
        <item>Discovery to delivery handoff: turning interview transcripts into structured backbone and tasks before sprint planning.</item>
        <item>Onboarding a new contributor who needs to understand the product end-to-end in one diagram.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Single isolated feature with no journey (e.g. "add audit log endpoint") — go directly to a story or spec.</item>
        <item>Maintenance / bug-fix work where the journey is already stable and mapped.</item>
        <item>Linear data-pipeline products with no user-facing journey; use technical sequence diagrams instead.</item>
        <item>When the team will not maintain the map — stale story maps actively mislead.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="backbone">
      <p>The backbone is the left-to-right spine of the map, representing the user's journey through key activities in chronological order.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use verb phrases for backbone activities; arrange left-to-right in user journey order; limit to 5-10 items.</statement>
        <rationale>Noun-only labels ("Project") lose the action context the team needs. More than 10 activities collapses into a Gantt chart and loses strategic clarity.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <note>E-commerce backbone: Browse Products → View Product → Add to Cart → Checkout → Receive Order</note>
      </example>
      <example type="bad">
        <note>Backbone labelled "Products, Cart, Payment, Order" — nouns only, no journey verb.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="user-tasks">
      <p>Tasks are the vertical cells under each backbone activity, ordered top-to-bottom by priority within that column. Each task represents work the user performs within that activity.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Place user tasks vertically under each backbone activity, ordered top-to-bottom by priority within that column. Every task must be user-observable, not an implementation step.</statement>
        <rationale>Vertical position encodes priority within an activity. "Authenticate user" is an implementation step; "Sign in with email" is user-observable.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Include at least one error or recovery task per backbone column.</statement>
        <rationale>Happy-path-only maps under-deliver; error flows are discovered after launch rather than before.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="walking-skeleton">
      <p>The walking skeleton is the minimum set of tasks that span the entire journey end-to-end, covering every backbone activity with one essential task. It defines the MVP boundary.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Identify exactly one task per backbone activity for the walking skeleton. The skeleton must span every column — gaps mean the journey cannot be completed end-to-end.</statement>
        <rationale>A skeleton missing one column produces an MVP that fails at that step. Completeness is non-negotiable.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <note>Walking skeleton for e-commerce: See product list | See details | Add item | Enter payment | Get confirmation — one task per activity, all five columns covered.</note>
      </example>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Walking skeleton silently dropped because "nothing felt minimal" for one activity.</description>
        <reason>Every activity exists because the user must complete it. If no task is minimal there, the activity itself is wrong.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="release-slices">
      <p>Release slices are horizontal groupings of tasks that deliver standalone user value. Each slice represents a shippable release, not a feature list.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Draw horizontal lines grouping tasks into shippable releases. Each slice must deliver standalone user value — it is not just a list of features.</statement>
        <rationale>A slice that depends on a later slice for value is not a release; it is a phase. Phases are not shippable.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Limit to 3-5 release slices. More than 5 destroys release thinking and turns the map into a roadmap.</statement>
        <rationale>Beyond 5 slices the distinction between releases blurs and planning reverts to feature-list mode.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <note>Release 1 for e-commerce: Filter by category | See images | Update quantity | Enter shipping | Email receipt — one thin horizontal slice per activity, all columns covered.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="story-mapping-process">
      <p>Building an effective story map requires five sequential steps, from framing the journey through slicing releases.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Before writing any activity, define: who is the user, what is their big goal, and where does the journey start and end. Input persona brief before mapping.</statement>
        <rationale>Without persona context, agents and workshop participants produce generic backbones ("View", "Browse", "Manage") that fit nothing specific.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Build the backbone first, collaboratively, with at least one user-voice input (interview notes count). Get backbone approval before generating tasks — backbone errors propagate to every task under them.</statement>
        <rationale>Skipping the backbone workshop and jumping to tasks is the number-one failure mode in story mapping.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Backbone drifts toward implementation steps: "Authenticate user", "Query database".</description>
        <reason>Backbone activities must be user-observable life events, not system operations.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <rule>
        <statement>For each activity, write every task the user does there. Arrange vertically by priority. Include at least one error/recovery/abandonment path per column.</statement>
        <rationale>Happy-path-only maps surface incomplete releases; error paths discovered post-launch cost more to fix.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Cap at 5 tasks per column before requiring justification. More than 5 per column signals the activity is too broad and should be split.</statement>
        <rationale>Uncapped task generation produces 50+ cards; column density above 5 degrades the visual signal the map is meant to provide.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Draw a line after the single minimum task in each column. Verify the line crosses every column. Name the skeleton explicitly ("walking_skeleton") in any structured data format.</statement>
        <rationale>An unnamed skeleton gets ignored during release planning. Explicit naming forces the team to acknowledge it as the MVP boundary.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Name each release with a value statement, not a version number. Validate: "Is this shippable to users as-is?" If no, the slice is too thin or incomplete.</statement>
        <rationale>Version numbers carry no product meaning; value statements ("Users can search and buy") communicate scope to all stakeholders.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Store the map as structured data (JSON/YAML), not only as a whiteboard image. Agents and humans both need the map queryable.</statement>
        <rationale>Whiteboard images cannot be updated from analytics data or referenced by downstream tools (backlog importers, sprint planners).</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good">
        <note>Release named "Customers can complete a purchase end-to-end" — value statement. Clear scope for all stakeholders.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="bad">
        <note>Release named "v1.2" — carries no product meaning; team must read the task list to understand scope.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-workflow">
      <p>A discovery agent ingests interview notes or journey maps and emits backbone activities (5–10). A task generator expands each activity into user tasks and ranks them vertically by impact. A slicer agent draws the walking skeleton and proposes 2–3 release slices, each with a value statement. A reviewer agent checks for end-to-end completeness (every activity has a skeleton task, no gaps). Human approves the backbone before tasks are generated — getting the backbone wrong propagates errors downward.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Backbone exploding to 15+ activities — the map turns into a Gantt chart and loses strategic clarity.</item>
        <item>Walking skeleton missing one column entirely; the agent or author skipped an activity because nothing felt minimal there. Walking skeleton must be end-to-end.</item>
        <item>Treating the map as static; user behaviour and analytics should rewrite vertical priorities monthly.</item>
        <item>Solo mapping by an agent without user research input produces happy-path-only maps, missing error/recovery flows.</item>
        <item>Confusing the map with a backlog. The map is journey-shaped; the backlog is rank-shaped. Both are needed.</item>
      </list>
      <rule testable="false">
        <statement>Without persona context, agents produce generic backbones ("View", "Browse", "Manage") that fit nothing. Always inject a persona brief.</statement>
        <rationale>Persona grounding forces agents to think about concrete user behavior instead of generic feature lists.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="false">
        <statement>Backbones drift toward implementation steps ("Authenticate user" instead of "Sign up"). Add a constraint that activities must be user-observable.</statement>
        <rationale>Implementation details hide the user's intent and break the journey narrative.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="false">
        <statement>Walking skeleton is silently dropped because it is "minimal" — explicitly require the slice "walking_skeleton" to exist and cover every column.</statement>
        <rationale>Without explicit naming, agents skip naming the skeleton and it becomes invisible during planning.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="false">
        <statement>Error/recovery tasks are routinely missing; tell the agent to allocate at least one error path per backbone column.</statement>
        <rationale>Happy-path-only maps surface during post-launch support, at much higher cost.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="false">
        <statement>Vertical priority is collapsed to monotonic 1..N which loses meaning; ask for tier (must/should/could) instead.</statement>
        <rationale>Numeric ranking without tier categories loses the signal about what is truly essential.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="false">
        <statement>Generated story cards often duplicate "As a user, I want to use the feature so that I can use it." Reject self-referential stories and force a measurable "so that".</statement>
        <rationale>Self-referential outcomes signal the agent did not understand the actual user goal.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="false">
        <statement>Agents will happily emit 50 task cards; cap with a hard maximum and require justification for exceeding 5 per column.</statement>
        <rationale>Uncapped output overwhelms the map's visual communication purpose.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/story-map.md" purpose="Story map template: context, backbone table, walking skeleton, release slices, parking lot."/>
      <template path="templates/story-card.md" purpose="Individual user story card with placement, acceptance criteria, and dependencies."/>
    </templates>

